Hey disturbed cook from san fransisco "never braise boneless skinless blah blah blah YUCK"... I did just what you consider reprehensible, and "why bother", and mine probably turned out better than yours... very tender and juicy. Perhaps you don't know as much as you like to think you do (or at least stop trying to sound like you know it all). Please just critic YOURSELF and how YOUR version ended up instead of putting down others. FYI for those of you who are sceptical about making this without skins or bones... what worked for ME, was to add two tablespoons of butter and approx 1/2cup (give or take a couple tablespoons)chicken broth after the initial browning. If you quickly brown the chicken at a high enough temp, it will NOT dry out. I was liberal with the salt and pepper on the breasts prior to browning, and I added kosher salt toward the end of the whole process. Delicious, even the second day! Worked for me!

Rating: 3
True confession - I have not made this recipe, but I wanted to share my best chicken recipe, which is similar, but much easier. Using a casserole dish, coat the bottom with equal parts lemon juice and olive oil (I probably use 1/4 ~ 1/2 cup of each). In that mix, put 1-2 head of peeled garlic cloves and any herbs you like. Lay chicken pieces over the top (I've used leg quarters, breasts, anything works) and cover the whole casserole with foil. Bake at 400 for 1 hour, and at the end, remove the foil to allow the chicken to brown and the skin to crisp. Your chicken will be juicy and tender and delicious, and it's so easy to roast some potatoes with oil and garlic and rosemary at the same time. Yum!

